We roll a fair 6-sided die 5 times.  What is the probability that we get a 6 in at most 2 of the rolls?
(A) \frac{625}{647}
(B) \frac{625}{648}

I have two cubes such that, on each cube, three faces are painted red and three faces are painted white. If I roll each of the cubes once, what is the probability that they will land such that there is one red face and one white face up?
(A) \frac{-1}{2}
(B) \frac{1}{2}

Congruent segments are used to form equilateral triangles in this sequence so that each figure contains one more triangle than the preceding figure. Figure 3 of the sequence is made with seven congruent segments. How many congruent segments must be used to make Figure 25 of the sequence?

[asy]
draw((0,0)--(10,0)--(5,8.7)--cycle);
draw((15,0)--(25,0)--(30,8.7)--(20,8.7)--cycle);
draw((20,8.7)--(25,0));
draw((35,0)--(55,0)--(50,8.7)--(40,8.7)--cycle);
draw((40,8.7)--(45,0)--(50,8.7));
draw((60,0)--(80,0)--(85,8.7)--(65,8.7)--cycle);
draw((65,8.7)--(70,0)--(75,8.7)--(80,0));
label("Figure 1",(2,0),S);
label("Figure 2",(20,-10),S);
label("Figure 3",(45,0),S);
label("Figure 4",(76,-10),S);
[/asy]
(A) 49
(B) 51

A turn consists of rolling a standard die and tossing a fair coin. The game is won when the die shows a 1 or a 6 and the coin shows heads. What is the probability the game will be won before the fourth turn? Express your answer as a common fraction.
(A) \dfrac{91}{218}
(B) \dfrac{91}{216}

There are four red balls and two white balls in a jar. One ball is randomly removed and replaced with a ball of the opposite color. The jar is then shaken and one ball is randomly selected. What is the probability that this ball is red? Express your answer as a common fraction.
(A) \frac{11}{18}
(B) \frac{11}{16}

What is the value of $(8-4)!\div(8-3)!$? Express your answer as a common fraction.
(A) \frac{3}{5}
(B) \frac{1}{5}

The fourth degree polynomial equation $x^4 - 7x^3 + 4x^2 + 7x - 4 = 0$ has four real roots, $a$, $b$, $c$ and $d$. What is the value of the sum $\frac{1}{a}+\frac{1}{b}+\frac{1}{c}+\frac{1}{d}$? Express your answer as a common fraction.
(A) \frac{7}{2}
(B) \frac{7}{4}

Compute the infinite sum $S,$ where
\[S = \frac{1}{2} - \frac{2}{4} + \frac{3}{8} - \frac{4}{16} + \frac{5}{32} - \dots + \frac{n}{2^n} (-1)^{n + 1} + \dotsb.\]
(A) \frac{4}{9}
(B) \frac{2}{9}

Compute $$\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{n}{n^4+n^2+1}.$$
(A) \frac{2}{2}
(B) \frac{1}{2}

There exists a polynomial $P$ of degree 5 with the following property: If $z$ is a complex number such that $z^5 + 2004z = 1,$ then $P(z^2) = 0.$  Calculate
\[\frac{P(1)}{P(-1)}.\]
(A) -\frac{2010012}{2010013}
(B) -\frac{2010011}{2010013}

